{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/gaussian-mixture-models-gmm-6e95cbc38e6e", "time": 1683006269.8551722, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/gaussian-mixture-models-gmm-6e95cbc38e6e/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Gaussian Mixture Models(GMM). Understanding GMM: Idea, Maths, EM\u2026 | by Ribhu Nirek | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Gaussian Mixture Models(GMM)", "description": "Brief: Gaussian mixture models is a popular unsupervised learning algorithm. The GMM approach is similar to K-Means clustering algorithm, but is more robust and therefore useful due to\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://medium.com/analytics-vidhya/k-means-clustering-algorithm-ea66d7ef4888", "anchor_text": "K-Means clustering", "paragraph_index": 1}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution", "anchor_text": "normal distribution", "paragraph_index": 1}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exploratory_data_analysis", "anchor_text": "exploratory data analysis", "paragraph_index": 1}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expectation\u2013maximization_algorithm", "anchor_text": "Expectation Maximization(EM) algorithm", "paragraph_index": 7}, {"url": "https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/351549/maximum-likelihood-estimators-multivariate-gaussian", "anchor_text": "MLE\u2019s", "paragraph_index": 9}, {"url": "https://scikit-learn.org/stable/tutorial/index.html", "anchor_text": "sklearn", "paragraph_index": 17}, {"url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/ribhu-nirek/", "anchor_text": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/ribhu-nirek/", "paragraph_index": 21}], "all_paragraphs": ["Brief: Gaussian mixture models is a popular unsupervised learning algorithm. The GMM approach is similar to K-Means clustering algorithm, but is more robust and therefore useful due to sophistication. In this article, I will be giving a birds-eye view, mathematics(bayesic maths, nothing abnormal), python implementation from scratch and also using sklearn library.", "It would be a good idea to check out my blog on K-Means clustering(3 min read) to get a basic idea of clustering, unsupervised learning and the K-means technique. In clustering, given an unlabelled dataset X, we wish to group the samples into K clusters. In GMMs, it is assumed that different sub-populations(K in total) of X follow a normal distribution, although we only have information about the probability distribution of the overall population X(hence the name Gaussian Mixture Model). Our task is to able to find the parameters of the K gaussian\u2019s in order to visualize the data X for exploratory data analysis or make predictions on new data.", "K-means uses the euclidean distance function to discover clusters in the data. This approach works well as long as the data follows a circular distribution with respect to centroids. But what if the data is non-linear, ellipsoidal? Or data has a non-zero covariance? What if clusters have different mean and covariances?", "This is where Gaussian Mixture Models save the day!", "GMM assumes a mixture of gaussian distributions to have generated the data. It uses with soft-assignment of data points to clusters(i.e. probabilistic and therefore better) contrasting with the K-means approach of hard-assignments of data points to clusters with the assumption of a circular distribution of data around centroids.", "In short, GMM capture works better because (A) it captures the uncertainty of data points belonging to different clusters by using soft-assignments, and (B) it doesn\u2019t have a bias for circular clusters. So, it works well even with non-linear data distributions.", "Objective function of GMM is to maximize the likelihood value for the data X, p(X) or the log-likelihood value L(since log is a monotonically increasing function). By assuming a mixture of K gaussians to have generated the data, we can write p(X) as marginalized probability, summed over all K clusters for all data points.", "With the summation inside the log function above, we cannot obtain an analytical solution. As nasty as it looks, there is an elegant solution to this problem: Expectation Maximization(EM) algorithm.", "The EM algorithm is an iterative algorithm used to find maximum likelihood estimates(MLE) of models where parameters cannot be found directly just like our case here. It consists of two steps: expectation step and the maximization step.", "2. Maximization Step: Calculate a new parameter mc, which determines the fraction of points belonging to different clusters. Update the parameters \u03bc, \u03c0, \u03a3 by calculating MLE\u2019s for each cluster c.", "Repeat the E-M steps until log-likelihood value L converges.", "Let\u2019s write a basic implementation for GMM in python from scratch.", "Run first iteration of the EM algorithm.", "Put this code in a for loop and box it in a class object. Now we are talking!", "We have a model up and running for 1-D data. Same principle works for higher dimensions(\u2265 2D) as well. Only difference is that we will using the multivariate gaussian distribution in this case. Let\u2019s write code for a 2D model.", "Let\u2019s generate some data and write our model.", "Let\u2019s make some prediction on this model.", "Using sklearn, the same task can be done within a few lines of code. Pretty slick, huh?", "So, GMM classifies the sample to belong to the second cluster. It works!", "Implementing Gaussian Mixture Models is not that difficult. Once you\u2019re clear with the math, it is finding Maximum likelihood estimates for the model whether its 1D or higher-dimensional data. This method is robust and useful in performing clustering tasks. Now that you are familiar with the python implementation of GMMs, you can perform cool stuffs with data sets. Suppose you are given a data set of patients consisting of two parameters: RBC Volume and RBC Hemoglobin Concentration without the labels of sick and healthy patients. Plugging the above model to cluster the data will give you two distinct(almost) masses which you can use for further analysis and predictions.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "MS, UMD | Amateur Writer | Mindfulness | https://www.linkedin.com/in/ribhu-nirek/"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F6e95cbc38e6e&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fgaussian-mixture-models-gmm-6e95cbc38e6e&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fgaussian-mixture-models-gmm-6e95cbc38e6e&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fgaussian-mixture-models-gmm-6e95cbc38e6e&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fgaussian-mixture-models-gmm-6e95cbc38e6e&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"